<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong> BUFFETTâS WARNING ON BANKS</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Warren E. Buffett has long ridiculed the financial industry. But his annual letter to shareholders âseemed to amp up the pugnacity and was clearly noted by the industry,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/03/business/a-warning-from-buffett-about-banks.html">Andrew Ross Sorkin writes in the DealBook column</a>. Mr. Buffett used his letter, published over the weekend, to warn his followers about âthe Streetâs denizens.â He criticized investment bankers for urging acquirers to pay up to 50 percent premiums over market price for publicly held businesses and railed against spinoffs.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âNo doubt, Mr. Buffett speaks the truth. There are countless examples of the build-it-up-and-tear-it-down phenomenon,â Mr. Sorkin writes. âBut as Mr. Buffett often points out the foibles of the finance industry, he also extols the personal virtues of some of the biggest names in investment banking. Berkshire owns a stake in Goldman Sachs, and Mr. Buffett has talked publicly about owning shares of JPMorgan Chase in his own account.â He has praised Lloyd C. Blankfein, Goldmanâs chief executive, and Jamie Dimon, the chief executive of JPMorgan.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What explains Mr. Buffettâs stance on the industry? One investment banker and blogger <a href="//epicureandealmaker.blogspot.com/2015/03/uncle-warren-explains-it-all-to-you.html">wrote over the weekend</a> that Mr. Buffett âdespises investment bankers and employs his considerable folksy charm to scare potential business sellers away from using us for the plain and simple reason that we make his job harder and more expensive.â For his part, Mr. Buffett, when reached at his office in Omaha, explained that he was <b>trying to educate his shareholders</b>. âThereâs nothing wrong with looking at the biases of a given field,â he said.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong> JPMORGAN TILTS TOWARD CONSUMER SIDE</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The diverging prospects for JPMorgan Chaseâs biggest businesses â its investment and consumer banks â reflect a split within the broader financial industry, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/03/business/dealbook/at-jpmorgan-chase-business-tilts-toward-consumer-side-and-away-from-wall-st.html">DealBookâs Nathaniel Popper writes</a>. Investors are betting that banks like Wells Fargo and U.S. Bancorp, which focus primarily on American consumers, will grow much faster than firms like Goldman Sachs, which are concentrated on Wall Street business. The division at JPMorgan Chase is so apparent that Gordon Smith, the chief of the consumer bank, is said to be in line to succeed Jamie Dimon, according to company executives.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âJPMorgan is a <b>particularly stark indication of the trends</b> because it has maintained dominant operations in both consumer and investment banking,â Mr. Popper writes. The investment bank, led by Daniel Pinto, has been improving its position relative to competitors, gaining market share in areas like stock trading and European banking, cementing its place as the worldâs biggest investment bank. But while profits at JPMorgan Chase rose to a record level last year, profits from the investment bank fell 16 percent from the previous year to the lowest level since 2011. When judged by returns it provides to shareholders, the investment bank has become the worst performing major division in the company.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The gap between the different businesses inside JPMorgan is a big part of the reason an analyst at Goldman Sachs suggested that the company might be worth more if the investment bank were broken off as a separate business. JPMorganâs executives push back against any suggestion that the bank should be split up, but the lagging performance is forcing Mr. Pinto to <b>consider cutting expenses more sharply</b> than other divisions of the company must. The situation has been brought on by several factors, including regulatory pressure and continuing low interest rates, which have reduced activity on trading desks across the industry. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
