<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>BARCLAYS POSTS ANNUAL LOSS</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Lower income in its investment bank and charges related to potential fines and litigation costs <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/04/business/dealbook/barclays-falls-to-annual-loss-on-litigation-charges.html">dragged Barclays to a loss in 2014</a>, the bank said on Tuesday. The bankâs annual results included 2.8 billion pounds, or about $4.3 billion, in litigation and conduct charges. That included Â£750 million in the fourth quarter related to continuing investigations into the potential manipulation of foreign currency trading markets, bringing the total set aside for 2014 to about Â£1.25 billion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For the year ended Dec. 31, Barclays <b>reported a net loss of Â£174 million</b>, compared with a profit of Â£540 million in 2013. Excluding the legal provisions and other one-time charges, Barclays said its full-year pretax profit had risen 12 percent to Â£5.5 billion from Â£4.9 billion in 2013. The adjusted results exceeded analystsâ expectations. For the fourth quarter, the bank posted a loss of Â£1.68 billion, from a loss of Â£642 million in the period a year earlier. Operating expenses declined 10 percent, to Â£16 billion, in 2014, from Â£17.8 billion in the previous year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Antony P. Jenkins, the Barclays chief executive, received total compensation of Â£5.47 million in 2014, including a bonus of Â£1.1 million. He turned down a bonus in 2013, citing the lenderâs continued restructuring and litigation expenses. The bankâs bonus awards for 2014 declined 22 percent to Â£1.86 billion in 2014.</p>
